1

A

  • Input : Often multidimensional, in which each dimension is referred to as a feature, predictor, or independent variable
  • Output : The response or dependent variable

B

  • use lm() to find the simple linear regression model?
  • lm(formula, data, ...) where the formula looks like Y~X, data is an optional argument
  • \(_0\) and \(_1\) are two unknown constants that represent the intercept and slope terms in the linear model. Together, 0 and 1 are known as the model coefficients or parameters.
  • These \(_0\) (Intercept) and \(_1\) (Top10perc) are those that minimize RSS and yield the least squares regression line.
lm.fit = lm(formula = Outstate ~ Top10perc, data = College)
lm.fit

Call:
lm(formula = Outstate ~ Top10perc, data = College)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)    Top10perc  
     6906.5        128.2

D

  • confidence intervals for \(B_0\) and \(B_1\)
confint(lm.fit, level = 0.95)
                2.5 %    97.5 %
(Intercept) 6471.4241 7341.4931
Top10perc    114.9459  141.5415

E

  • point estimate
  • the c() is combine, it is creating a list of the x values
lm.pointEst = predict(lm.fit, data.frame(Top10perc = c(0.33)))
lm.pointEst
       1 
6948.779
  • confidence interval
confint(lm.pointEst, level = 0.95)
Error: $ operator is invalid for atomic vectors

F

  • plotting lm.fit using geom_jitter() and geom_smooth()
ggplot(data = lm.fit, mapping = aes(x=Top10perc, y=Outstate)) + geom_jitter() + geom_smooth(method='lm', formula= y~x) + theme_bw()

2

A

  • The null hypothesis is a specific statement about a population parameter that is made for the purposes of argument. A good null hypothesis is something that would be interesting to reject, and thus is uninteresting. (slide 102 in LR p1)
  • The alternative hypothesis includes all possible values for the population parameter aside from the one stated by the null hypothesis. The alternative hypothesis is what the researcher hopes is true, and thus is interesting. (slide 103 in LR p1)

B

  • We can view all of the output of lm() with the summary() function using summary()
  • test statistic
